          <h2 id="about-the-scheme">About the scheme</h2>

<p>Poultry keepers can claim £430 for a vet to do a poultry biosecurity review. Reviews include all eligible species kept on a site.</p>

<p>If multiple sites need reviews, £430 funding will be given for each site.</p>

<p>These are the steps poultry keepers need to take.</p>

<ol class="steps">
  <li>
    <p>
      <strong>Apply for an agreement by 30 September 2028</strong>
    </p>
    <p>Read the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/laying-hen-housing-for-health-and-welfare-grant-round-1/terms-and-conditions">terms and conditions</a> before you apply for an agreement.</p>

    <p>Each single business identifier (SBI) will have one agreement, which can include:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>any eligible species</li>
      <li>multiple poultry sites</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Arrange for a vet review to take place by 31 December 2028</strong></p>

    <p>You must have an agreement in place before you organise a vet review.</p>
    <p>A review is complete when the vet has:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>done a biosecurity assessment</li>
      <li>downloaded and filled in a <a href="#">vet summary template</a></li>
      <li>written a report</li>
    </ul>

  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Claim funding by 31 March 2029 </strong></p>
    <p>A claim can only be made when you have the vet summary.</p>
    <p>A claim must be submitted in the same financial year that the review took place. For example, if a review takes place in November 2027, the claim must be submitted by 31 March 2028.</p>
    <p>Funding will not be available after the service closes on 31 March 2029.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<h2 id="who-can-apply">Who can apply</h2>

<p>Poultry keepers are eligible to claim for a biosecurity review if they keep any of the following species:</p>

<ul>
  <li>1,000 or more broilers</li>
  <li>1,000 or more egg-laying hens</li>
  <li>1,000 or more breeders</li>
  <li>500 or more ducks</li>
  <li>500 or more geese</li>
  <li>500 or more turkeys</li>
</ul>

<p>Species numbers cannot be combined, for example 200 ducks and 300 turkeys.</p>

<p>If the site is empty, the vet must assess its capacity to hold the minimum number of relevant birds. This is based on stocking densities stated in the <a href="#">codes of practice for the welfare of poultry</a>.</p>

<p>A poultry keeper does not need to be the owner of the birds.</p>

<p>Poultry keepers must:</p>

<ul>
  <li>claim only for poultry registered in England</li>
  <li>be responsible for the welfare of their birds when the vet does a review</li>
  <li>claim only for a business which has an SBI linked to a county parish holding (CPH) number registered in England</li>
</ul>

{# <p>You can claim funding if you have set up a ‘Get funding to improve animal health and welfare’ (<abbr title="Improve Animal Health and Welfare">IAHW</abbr>) agreement before the vet visit. The vet will give you a summary of the animal health and welfare review or endemic disease follow-up.</p> #}

<h2 id="apply-or-make-a-claim">Apply or make a claim</h2>

<p>Use this service to apply for a Poultry Biosecurity Review agreement and make claims.</p>

<p>You will need your Rural Payments service customer reference number (CRN) and password to sign in.</p>

<h3>Apply for an agreement</h3>

<p>You need to apply for an agreement before you can make a claim. You only need to do this once for an SBI.</p>

<p>Applying takes about 5 to 10 minutes.</p>

<h3>Make a claim</h3>

<p>You will need to use the details given in the vet's summary when making a claim.</p>

{# <p>Claiming takes about 10 minutes.</p> #}

<p><a class="gem-c-button govuk-button govuk-button--start" role="button" data-module="govuk-button" data-ga4-attributes="{&quot;event_name&quot;:&quot;navigation&quot;,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;start button&quot;}" draggable="false" href="https://apply-for-an-annual-health-and-welfare-review.defra.gov.uk/sign-in" data-govuk-button-init="" data-govuk-button-module-started="true"><span> Start now </span><svg class="govuk-button__start-icon govuk-!-display-none-print" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="17.5" height="19" viewBox="0 0 33 40" focusable="false" aria-hidden="true"><path fill="currentColor" d="M0 0h13l20 20-20 20H0l20-20z"></path></svg></a></p>


<h2 id="how-to-have-a-poultry-biosecurity-review">How to have a poultry biosecurity review</h2>

<p>Poultry keepers can choose the vet they want to do a review.</p>

<p>If you are a poultry keeper who is a vet, you cannot carry out your own review – you must use another vet.</p>

<p>As part of an agreement, poultry keepers can have a poultry biosecurity review:</p>

<ul>
  <li>every 10 months</li>
  <li>a maximum of 3 times</li>
</ul>

<p>Reviews must be completed by 31 December 2028.</p>

<h3>What a review includes</h3>

<p>Reviews can take place in a single visit or over several visits.</p>

<p>The vet's biosecurity assessment should cover:</p>

<ul>
  <li>infrastructure and location</li>
  <li>organisation of site and supply of materials</li>
  <li>visitors, personnel and hygiene locks</li>
  <li>buying in poultry</li>
  <li>depopulation and off-farm movement of birds</li>
  <li>transportation and management of eggs</li>
  <li>feed and water supply</li>
  <li>manure and carcass removal</li>
  <li>disease management</li>
  <li>cleaning and disinfection</li>
  <li>measures between compartments and houses</li>
</ul>

<p>Vets can use free online tools to help with assessments, such as <a href="https://biocheck.ugent.be/">biocheck.ugent</a> and the <a href="https://britishpoultry.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/examples-of-biosecurity-practices.pdf">British Poultry Council's biosecurity photobook</a>.</p>

<h3>What vets needs to provide</h3>

<p>After an assessment, vets must give the poultry keeper:</p>
<ul>
  <li>a vet summary using our <a href="#">downloadable template</a></li>
  <li>a written report of the assessment and recommended actions</li>
</ul>

<p>The details given in the vet's summary will be used to make a claim.</p>

<p>The Department for Environment, Food & Rural Affairs (Defra) and Rural Payments Agency (RPA) will not ask to see the written report.</p>



